1. Introduction
Some universities including Augustana University allow the majority of their
students(Especially ones living on campus) to utilize the central mailing address for the school to
receive all mail, and later distribute the mail to each student based on the box number they own.
But right now, the distribution system is not efcient. Important mails may not be retrieved
for months just because the student who received the mail is not notied on arrival. Students
have to repeatedly, or regularly check their box in order to not miss important mails.
But that should not be the case in todays world of automated systems. And this is exactly
the problem what this web application is supposed to x. This web app gives the postmaster of
the schools access to a database that stores new mail arrivals as records. Students then can use a
properly designed and implemented website to access the database in an efcient manner. Future
implementations may include students setting their accounts to push access instead of a pull,
so that they can receive notications for new mail even without even checking the site. But even
with the current pull access (checking the website for update themselves just by logging on), the
major drawback of the existing system (which is taking a trip to the physical mailbox) is solved.
2. Technologies used
Database - Mongodb
Server side - Node.js(server side javascript)
Front End - HTML(EJS template), CSS and JS(client side)

2.2. Server Side
Node.js is used for server side design. Node handles all the routes using express,
authenticates users(students) using passport and Google OAuth 2.0, and nally renders all
the templates to HTML using EJS. Here are some dependencies(Modules) I mainly used:
Express & EJS - routing and templating
!3
Users collection
Mails collection
Passport and Google OAuth - authentication by using google APIs(It limits access
to email domains with @ole.augie.edu- Augustana students)
Mongoose - connecting to the Mongodb server. MLabs connection to Mongoose
is as simple as pasting a link.
2.3. Front End
Front end gets rendered to HTML using EJS. Express also assigns a specic folder for
all the static JS, CSS and Image les called public.
A. Bootstrap
Majority of the site uses bootstrap css and js as a front end framework.
It helps in great deal to make the site responsive(Fluid layout and overall
design to make the site user friendly across many devices; including
Smartphones, tablets and desktops)
It also includes pre-dened classes to make the styling of forms, buttons
and other HTML elements easy and at the same time responsive(see above
bullet point).
B. EJS
Although its a Node.js feature, it has more to do with the front end
programming of the side than it has to do with the server side.
It connects the server side to the client side(front end).
Unlike HTML, it uses partials to only code repetitive page structures
once(like headers, footers), and render them multiple times dynamically.
!4
